---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import PageHero from '../components/PageHero.astro';
import RegMark from '../components/RegMark.astro';
import { codex } from '../data/codex';

const inks = ['c', 'm', 'y'];
---

<Base
  title="About"
  description="Jo Murgel — trained as an artist, working as an engineer, thinking like an architect. The longer, weirder version."
  heroInk="y"
>
  <PageHero
    ink="y"
    title="About"
    lede="Trained as an artist, working as an engineer, thinking like an architect. Here's the longer, weirder version."
  />

  <section class="about-lead">
    <figure class="about-photo">
      <div class="photo-placeholder" role="img" aria-label="Portrait of Jo — coming soon">
        <RegMark size={44} />
        <span>Portrait — coming soon</span>
      </div>
    </figure>
    <div class="about-intro">
      <p>
        I came to engineering sideways. Three art degrees first — graphic design, illustration,
        and photography — then about fifteen years building for the web, from frontend to principal
        to leading teams. Turns out the art degrees weren't a waste of anyone's money: they're why I
        care as much about how a thing is <em>designed</em> as whether it ships, and why I'd rather
        hunt down the actual problem than glue a template over it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The most-watched movie of my childhood was Mike Jitlov's <em><a href="https://wizworld.com" target="_blank">
        The Wizard of Speed and Time</a></em> — one obsessive artist hand-building impossible effects out of nothing
        but ingenuity and craft. I didn't clock it at the time, but that was the whole blueprint: make something dazzling, do it
        yourself, solve the problem in a way nobody else would. Everything since has been a remix of that.
      </p>
      <p>
        These days that shows up as a few overlapping things — maker, engineer, artist, photographer —
        which are really one instinct wearing different clothes. When I'm not doing the day-job version,
        I'm doing some lower-stakes one: shooting flowers, gutting a bathroom that never fit me, or
        arguing with a 3D printer. If you're after the professional version, that lives over on
        <a href="/work">Work</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section class="codex" aria-labelledby="codex-heading">
    <div class="codex-head">
      <h2 id="codex-heading">The Codex</h2>
      <p class="section-lede">All the other stuff that informs who I am — a living, over-long list of things I love.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="codex-grid">
      {codex.map((c, i) => (
        <div class="codex-cat" data-ink={inks[i % 3]}>
          <h3>{c.label}</h3>
          {c.intro && <p class="codex-intro">{c.intro}</p>}
          <ul>
            {c.items.map((it) => (
              <li class:list={[{ 'is-done': it.done }]}>
                {it.url ? <a href={it.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">{it.name}</a> : it.name}
                {it.note && <span class="codex-note"> — {it.note}</span>}
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <figure class="codex-gif">
      <img src="/codex/feed.gif" alt="The Owl House — 'And now, we feed.'" loading="lazy" width="600" height="338" />
      <figcaption>
        My favorite <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bmqy-Sp0txY" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ʒaɪf</a>.
        Yes, that's how it's pronounced — I have receipts.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>
</Base>
